        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="601" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d601">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.2423/1–546</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                            State</gloss> to President <persName type="to">Truman</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-05">January 5,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The British have requested that a British scientific team be permitted to attend
                    the forthcoming atomic bomb trials.<note n="4" xml:id="d601fn4">For information
                        regarding the origins of the Bikini tests, see Hewlett and Anderson, pp.
                        581–582.</note> The Secretaries of State, War, and Navy approve the idea,
                    particularly since the British have various experts with special knowledge who
                    would be of considerable assistance in connection with the tests, and from the
                    military standpoint their participation would be desirable. The officer in
                    charge of the atomic bomb project<note n="5" xml:id="d601fn5">Vice Adm. William
                        H. P. Blandy.</note> has indicated informally that he has no objection.</p>
                <p>We should like to have your approval before proceeding.<note n="6" xml:id="d601fn6">The President’s initialled “OK” appears on the source
                        text.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James</hi> F. <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
